Introduction

Any analysis of association between genotype and phenotype starts with the collection of good phenotypic data and adequate statistical analysis for associating the phenotypic variation at the molecular level. In the last tutorial, we discussed the importance of using statistical methods to approach the phenotypic data. The second important piece of information is to obtain variants at the genetic level.

This tutorial addresses the importance of quantifying genetic variation at the population level. By genetic variation, we mean differences in DNA content or structure among individuals. As an example, it is estimated that there are more than 100,000,000 know genetic variants in the human genome. When such variations are accessed, we can, for example, differente humans based on genetic information. Variation at the DNA level can be classified in different ways, including as Single-nucleotide polymorphims (SNPs), insertion-deletion polymorphisms (indels) and structural variants (SV).

Quantify such variation by measuring allelic variations within a locus is called genotyping. We will not present details on how to obtain molecular markers for genotyping. But in general, the process of genotyping can be carried out using sequencig methods or arrays.

Sequencing methods we can divide in four main phases:

  1. sequencing and obtaining the FASTQ files;
  2. align to a reference genome;
  3. identify genetic variants;
  4. count the number of reads with each allele to perform the genotyping calling.
  • Examples of sequencing methods include whole-genome sequencing, GBS methods, CaptureSeq and other variations of GBS approach.

For genotyping array, we can also divide in four main stepes:

  1. each spot on array is targeting specific SNPs;
  2. DNA fragment attach to spot;
  3. each allele is labelled with a different color;
  4. fluorescence of both alleles are capture and used for genotyping calling.
  • Examples of arrays includes KASP markers, Sequenom MASSArray, Illumina GoldenGate.

Both methods have one task in common for polyploid analyses: after identified the genetic variants across the genome we need to compute the the allelic dosage to assign the genotypic class of a given individual. In this tutorial we will focus on sequencing methods, but the principle to assign allele dosages in arrays is very similar.

We will follow the general structure:

  • What is dosage?
  • Why is dosage calling more challenging in polyploids?
  • From raw data to dosage calling, how to define the genotypic class in tetraploid

Overview of Dosage Calling

Look the example below:

  • We are using a genotyping-by-sequencing method to differentiate 3 individuals
  • For this chr we could find 10 SNPs
  • We are investigating two loci (SNP4 and SNP10)
  • Diploid species (2n=2x)
  • Task: determine the genotype classes for the individuals for both loci

Observations

  • By dosage we mean the count of one allele at one marker (position) in one individual
  • The example refers to a diploid species
  • It seems clear that individual 1 is well genotyped for both SNPs, correct? There is good coverage of the sampled alleles.
  • And about the individual 2? For SNP4, the T allele, is it a true variation or perhaps a sequencing error? Would this genotype be homozygous or heterozygous? And about the SNP10, there is a low coverage !
  • Ind 3 was massively sequenced. When compared with Ind 1, for example, which of the two individuals for both SNPs are presenting more evidences about the real genotype?

Conclusion

  • Genotyping is equivalent to associating the allele dosage on a given locus to this genotype by considering the proportion of reference and alternative alleles sequenced.

Example sequencing data

See the example below:

Example of a good SNP

  • This scatterplot represents a single SNP, in blueberry.
  • Each point is an individual.
  • The x-axis is the number of âaâ reads and the y-axis is the number âAâ reads.
  • The five lines jutting out from (0,0) represent the expected counts at each of the five possible genotypes for a tetraploid individual.

Can you define the genotypes of each individual in the population?

  • The bottom right line is the expected counts for an individual with four copies of âaâ (aaaa), the next line up is for individuals with tree copies of âaâ (Aaaa), then two copies (AAaa), etc.
  • Common nomenclature:
    • quadruplex (AAAA),
    • triplex (Aaaa),
    • duplex (AAaa),
    • simplex (Aaaa),
    • nulliplex (aaaa)
  • Genotyping is equivalent to associating each point on this genotype plot with the line it belongs to. In the above plot, making this determination is relatively easy.
  • This example is simple, because this SNP has a good point cloud pattern within the expected lines. Technically, we donât need a statistical method to classify genotypes.

But there is no free lunch in Science â¦

And about the example below:

Example of bad SNPs

  • There is a confusion in the point cloud for the three SNPs under evaluation.
  • Which line do they belong?
  • SNPs with this messy pattern is very common in polyploid data sets.
  • We had to deal with some issues present in sequencing data: bias, overdispersion, and outlying points; that has biological and technical causes.

updog package

  • Updog provides a suite of methods for genotyping polyploids from next-generation sequencing (NGS) data. It does this while accounting for many common features of NGS data: allele bias, overdispersion, and sequencing error.
  • The method is described in detail Gerard et. al. (2018)
  • Additional details concerning prior specification are described in Gerard and FerrÃ£o (2020)
  • More intuive explanation you can find here
  • Github of the package.

The model

\[[\tilde{y}_i|\tilde{n}_j,\tilde{p}_j= l_j/K,\epsilon, h,\tau, \pi]\] \[\sim \pi BB(\tilde{n}_j, \xi (l_j/K,\epsilon,h),\tau) + (1-\pi)BB(N-j,1/2,1/3)\] \[\sum^{k_i}_{j=0} HG \left (j, \frac{k}{2} \mid l_1,K) HG(k_i-j, \frac{k}{2} | l_2,K \right)\] \[logit(\epsilon) \sim N(\mu_e,\sigma^2_e)\] \[log(h) \sim N(\mu_h, \sigma^2_h)\] Intuitively

  • In theory: software will estimate error, bias, overdispersion parameters
  • In practice: âAdjusting the expected anglesâ, given the data and estimated parameters

Why updog?

  • Allele dosage calling for any ploidy
  • Filter out poor SNPs/individuals
  • Estimate preferential paring
  • Multiple population designs (flexible prior distributions)
  • Simulate genotypes from NGS technologies
  • Programmed in R
  • Straightforward to run analysis in parallel
  • More than 17000 downloads
  • Standard method used for different research groups and genotyping companies

Admixture population

Overview about vcf files

  • Modern genotyping plataform output the results in a vcf format
  • vcf is a text file format that contains meta-information lines, a header line, and then data lines each containing information about a position in the genome.
  • Example in a diploid genotype (more detail here):
##fileformat=VCFv4.0 
##fileDate=20160306 
##source="Stacks v1.37"
##INFO=<ID=NS,Number=1,Type=Integer,Description="Number of Samples With Data"> 
##INFO=<ID=AF,Number=.,Type=Float,Description="Allele Frequency"> 
##FORMAT=<ID=GT,Number=1,Type=String,Description="Genotype"> 
##FORMAT=<ID=DP,Number=1,Type=Integer,Description="Read Depth"> 
##FORMAT=<ID=AD,Number=1,Type=Integer,Description="Allele Depth"> 
##FORMAT=<ID=GL,Number=.,Type=Float,Description="Genotype Likelihood"> 
#CHROM    POS    ID    REF    ALT    QUAL    FILTER    INFO    FORMAT    Parental_1    Parental_2    ID_1    ID_2    ID_3 
Chr02    5565755    44509    A    G    .    PASS    .    GT:DP:AD:GL    0/1:31:23,8:.,42.98,.    0/0:13:9,0:.,18.02,.    0/0:30:30,0:.,41.59,.    0/0:27:27,0:.,37.43,.    0/0:25:25,0:.,34.66,.
  • It is a SNP at chromosome 2 in the position 5565755.
  • Reference allele is an A and has one alternative allele G.
  • There is no information about the quality of this data collected. It passed through the filter criteria. There is no additional information about it.
  • Samples are represented in the order GT:DP:AD:GL (genotype, read depth, allele depth, and genotype likelihood).
  • For diploid analyses, in general, we are interested on the GT field
    • 0/1 = analogous to Aa
    • 0/0 = analogous to aa
    • 1/1 = analogous to AA

Software

  • vcf files can be very different depending of the software and parameter used to call the molecular markers.
  • vcf is much more informative than 012 formats. But for genomic selection, most of the softwares require SNPs the 012 format.
  • vcftools to run in terminal

  • vcfR to run in R

  • Suggestion: use vcftools !

Observation:

  • Alternative and reference alleles are called depending of the reference genome
  • ratio is a good alternative for genomic selection, in particular, if you have good sequencing depth and modeling a proxy for additive effects. For more details, see de Bem Oliveira et al., (2019) and FerrÃ£o et al., (2021).
  • You can use the ratio directly in the rrblup package for quick GWAS and GS anlyses. This is an interesting step for initial checks
  • Before running updog, you can remove genotypes with certain level of missing data, or SNPs with rare allele in the population just checking the ratiovalues. With that, you prevent updog from wasting computational time on bad quality SNPs

3. Running updog

  • Tutorial for more details about function and input.
  • We will run this example only for two SNPs
library(updog)
library(gridExtra)
library(ggplot2)
refmat  <- t(as.matrix(ref)) # dim: marker by individuals 
sizemat <- t(as.matrix(dp)) # dim: marker by individuals
ploidy  <- 4

dim(refmat)
## [1]   10 1790
# visualize the raw data
p1=plot_geno(refvec = refmat[1,], sizevec = sizemat[1,], ploidy = ploidy)+
  ggtitle("1_74957")

# Fitting updog
uout <- multidog(refmat = refmat[1:2,],  # only for the SNPq
                sizemat =  sizemat[1:2,],  # only for the SNPq
                model="norm",          # better model for admixture populations
                ploidy  = ploidy,
                nc=4) # number of clusters

4. Output from updog

  • snpdf: A data frame containing properties of the SNPs (markers). The rows index the SNPs
  • inddf: A data frame containing the properties of the individuals at each SNP.
  • bias: systematic bias toward reference or alternative allele.
  • sequencing error: homozygous individuals can be erroneously classified as heterozygous.
  • overdispersion: additional variability in the model
  • prop_miss: most important metric from updog and informs the (posterior) proportion of individuals mis-genotyped
library(updog)

Biparental Population

  • Population used in Cappai et al., (2020) for linkage mapping and QTL analyses of fruit firmness in blueberry
  • Model f1 in updog package
  • Prior assumes the individuals are all full-siblings. This model assumes a particular type of meiotic behavior: polysomic inheritance with bivalent, non-preferential pairing

Output from updog in a biparental family

Below the example of SNP with a good pattern.

Good SNP

Below one example of largebias with updog fitted with parental information (f1 model) and withou parental information (norm model). In this example, we used the flexdog() function, that is the same function of multidog(), but not in the parallel version.

# F1 model
uout <- flexdog(refvec = oref[snp,], 
          sizevec = osize[snp,],
          p1ref = oref[snp,"PAT_194201_P003_WH10"], # Information from the parental 1
          p1size=osize[snp,"PAT_194201_P003_WH10"],
          p2ref = oref[snp,"PAT_194201_P003_WH12"], # Information from the parental 2
          p2size=osize[snp,"PAT_194201_P003_WH12"],
          model   = "f1",   
          ploidy = 4, verbose=F)

uout2 <- flexdog(refvec = oref[snp,], 
          sizevec = osize[snp,],
          model   = "norm", 
          ploidy = 4, verbose=F)

Large bias

Some notes

  • SNP 1_4849891 presented the largest bias
  • Based on the raw data (right), one parental is AAAA and the other is aaaa.
  • However, one of the parental has >100 reads and the other <50 reads, which means they have different information levels (or, in the statistical term, less evidences).
  • Using mendelian segregation, we should not expect homozygous segregating.
  • This should be a monomorphic markers. Updogs is showing that, based on the population segregation, one of the parental should be AAAa.
  • This is an extreme case of bias.

Final notes

  • In diploids there is only one type of heterozygote, in polyploids there are multiple
  • Raw data from sequencing (read counts) or arrays (signal intensities) must be converted to allele dosages to be used in downstream analyses
  • Several software packages available
  • Genotyping array:
    • Allele are labelled with a different colors
    • Fluorescence of both labels measured
    • Example: KASP markers, Sequenom MASSArray, Illumina GoldenGate and others
    • Software: fitPoly (fitTetra), SuperMASSA and ClusterCall
  • Sequencing data:
    • Software: updog and polyRAD

  • Important information for blueberry studies.
  • Haplotype-phased blueberry genome was published by Colle et al., (2019).
